<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1670,2021]" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1670,1697]" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Bionomics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[340,463,1670,1697]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 2–8" captionStart-1="FIGURES 9–19" captionStartId-0="3.[151,264,1527,1552]" captionStartId-1="5.[151,264,1851,1876]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1435,181,1819]" captionTargetId-0="figure@3.[151,1438,368,1323]" captionTargetId-1="figure@5.[151,1435,181,1832]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 2–8. Habitat and host plants of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov. 2, 3, habitat, Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, 850 m, 3°45’58’’N, 76°40’43’’W; 4–8, host plant, Wedelia calycina Rich., Asteraceae (see Remarks)." captionText-1="FIGURES 9–19. Leaf mines of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov., Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, Colombia." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3407713/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3337705/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Figs. 2–19</figureCitation>
). The host plant is 
<taxonomicName authority="Rich." authorityName="Rich." box="[678,938,1670,1696]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Wedelia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="222" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calycina">
<emphasis box="[678,870,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Wedelia calycina</emphasis>
Rich.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[952,1081,1671,1697]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="3" pageNumber="222" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
: Heliantheae: Ecliptinae) (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 2–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1527,1552]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1438,368,1323]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2–8. Habitat and host plants of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov. 2, 3, habitat, Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, 850 m, 3°45’58’’N, 76°40’43’’W; 4–8, host plant, Wedelia calycina Rich., Asteraceae (see Remarks)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3407713/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Figs. 4–8</figureCitation>
). Mining larvae are recorded from February and early March. The blotch mine is irregular, usually dark, but with little irregularly deposited frass (
<figureCitation box="[578,702,1742,1769]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1851,1876]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1819]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,181,1832]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–19. Leaf mines of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov., Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, Colombia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3337705/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Figs. 9–19</figureCitation>
); fully developed mines sometimes may bend (distort) the mined leaf (
<figureCitation box="[209,346,1778,1805]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1851,1876]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1819]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,181,1832]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–19. Leaf mines of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov., Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, Colombia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3337705/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Figs. 18, 19</figureCitation>
); old vacant leaf mines usually appear pale brown or whitish brown. A silk-lined nidus is usually indistinct inside of the mine. The larva is pale yellowish green, with a dark green intestine and a blackish brown head (
<figureCitation box="[219,354,1850,1877]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1851,1876]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1819]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,181,1832]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 9–19. Leaf mines of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov., Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, Colombia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3337705/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Figs. 11, 14</figureCitation>
). Pupation occurs inside the leaf mine; the pupa is brown to grey-beige. An exit slit usually is on the upper side. Adults occur from February and late March.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="222" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1670,2021]" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1922,1949]" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Distribution</emphasis>
. The species is known from the single locality, Lobo Guerrero, 
<collectingRegion box="[1090,1275,1922,1949]" country="Colombia" name="Valle del Cauca" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Valle del Cauca</collectingRegion>
, southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,261,1958,1984]" name="Colombia" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[276,340,1958,1985]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1917,1942]" captionTargetBox="[333,1261,691,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[322,1262,680,1899]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Type locality of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov. (Lobo Guerrero) and A. ochrimaculosa Diškus, Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov. (El Naranjo) in Valle del Cauca, southwestern Colombia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3337703/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) at an elevation of about 
<quantity box="[622,695,1958,1985]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="222" unit="m" value="850.0">850 m</quantity>
, mostly from drier rocky slopes along an abandoned railway (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 2–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1527,1552]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1438,368,1323]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2–8. Habitat and host plants of Astrotischeria colombiana Stonis &amp; Vargas, sp. nov. 2, 3, habitat, Lobo Guerrero, Valle del Cauca, 850 m, 3°45’58’’N, 76°40’43’’W; 4–8, host plant, Wedelia calycina Rich., Asteraceae (see Remarks)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3407713/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="222">Figs. 2, 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="223" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,287]" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the country, 
<collectingCountry box="[784,898,152,178]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,189,215]" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">Remarks.</emphasis>
The host plant resembles some species of 
<taxonomicName authority="O. Hoffm." authorityName="O. Hoffm." box="[787,1070,188,215]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Sphagneticola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="223" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[787,947,188,214]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">Sphagneticola</emphasis>
O. Hoffm.
</taxonomicName>
(L. Katinas 
<emphasis box="[1207,1343,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">pers. comm.</emphasis>
) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">Ti- thonia</emphasis>
Desf. ex Juss. (E. Moreno 
<emphasis box="[519,655,225,250]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="223">pers. comm.</emphasis>
